75 % of working mothers have had professional problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Fécondity and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer reveals.
The survey, conducted out of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers saw their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushed back into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after joining a couple. This figure increases to 4.1 for those working in the public sector."These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the date of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those with elementary and higher education were mothers on average for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age.
"Another division also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher level studies invert this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," said Ms. Delgado.
