As has been done with the anti-lock system for ABS brakes and as will be done with the ESP stability control, emergency braking systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
Moreover, they are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a deficit period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, although, by its way of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system by the driver's step.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not support the brake before the collision, and half of them did not benefit from its full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, revancha, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularity of so-called emergency braking intelligent systems: it is estimated that one in four disaster with injured people would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to radar or camera, detects the obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize the damage.
